Hereafter, I will show how it cam be found.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;img alt="" src="http://gauss.geofisica.ufrn.br/~ionosfera/zedias/meteorologia/planck.png" style="float:right;width:80%;margin:10px" /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class="math"&gt;\begin{equation}
\label{eq1}
B(T,\lambda) = \frac{2hc^{2}}{\lambda^{5}(exp(\frac{hc}{kT})-1)}
\end{equation}&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;By simplicity, let's define &lt;span class="math"&gt;\(\alpha\equiv 2hc^{2}\)&lt;/span&gt; and &lt;span class="math"&gt;\(\gamma\equiv \frac{hc}{kT}\)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;So, the equation \ref{eq1} becomes &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class="math"&gt;\begin{equation}
\label{eq2}
B(T, \lambda) = D\lambda^{-5}(exp(\frac{B}{\lambda})-1)^{-1} 
\end{equation}&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;But what we want to find? We are interested to find in which wavelength occur 
the maximum emissivity. For it, we need to make &lt;span class="math"&gt;\(\frac{\partial B}{\partial \lambda}=0\)&lt;/span&gt;. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class="math"&gt;\begin{equation}
\begin{split}
 \frac{\partial B}{\partial \lambda}=D\lambda^{-6}(exp(\frac{B}{\lambda})-1)
[-5+ \\ B\lambda^{-1}(exp(\frac{B}{\lambda})-1)^{-1}exp(\frac{B}{\lambda})] =0
\end{split}
\label{eq3}
\end{equation}&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The solution of equation \ref{eq3} is getting doing the factor inside of brackets equal
to zero. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class="math"&gt;\begin{equation}
-5+ B\lambda^{-1}(exp(\frac{B}{\lambda})-1)^{-1}exp(\frac{B}{\lambda}) =0
\label{eq4}
\end{equation}&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;After to reorder all factors in \ref{eq4}, we will get the equation bellow.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class="math"&gt;\begin{equation}
\lambda[\exp(\frac{B}{\lambda})(\frac{B}{\lambda}-5)+5]=0
\label{eq5}
\end{equation}&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Once that &lt;span class="math"&gt;\(\lambda\)&lt;/span&gt; is different of zero, the factor inside of brackets has to be
zero. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class="math"&gt;\begin{equation}
exp(\frac{B}{\lambda})(\frac{B}{\lambda}-5)+5=0
\label{eq6}
\end{equation}&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The equation \ref{eq6} is a transcendental equation, it means that this 
isn't possible to solve by traditional way. By simplicity, we will define 
&lt;span class="math"&gt;\(g\equiv \frac{B}{\lambda}\)&lt;/span&gt;. So, the least equation becomes &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class="math"&gt;\begin{equation}
exp(g)(g-5)+5=0
\label{eq7}
\end{equation}&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;(I will finish it soon as possible.)&lt;/p&gt;
